  "why": "The AutoDAN design explicitly aims to preserve semantic meaning and naturalness across iterations and includes multiple mechanisms to enforce this: initialization from handcrafted prototype prompts, LLM-based diversification used both for initialization and as the mutation operator (which the authors state preserves global meaning), a low mutation rate, elitism that carries high-fitness prompts forward unchanged, and a momentum word-scoring scheme that stabilizes lexical changes across iterations. The paper also measures and reports sentence perplexity (PPL) of generated prompts and shows AutoDAN produces low-PPL (i.e., realistic, fluent) prompts comparable to handcrafted DAN and far lower than token-level baselines, and demonstrates robustness to perplexity-based defenses—evidence that semantic consistency and naturalness are enforced throughout the fuzzing process.",
  "evidence": "Sec. 3.2 Population Initialization (page 4): \"To preserve the basic features of the prototype handcrafted jailbreak prompt while also promoting diversification, we employ LLMs as the agents responsible for revising the prototype prompt...the modifications proposed by LLM can preserve the inherent logical flow and meaning of the original sentences...\"; Sec. 3.4 Paragraph-level selection (page 6): \"Given an elitism rate α, we first allow the top N * α prompts with the highest fitness scores to directly proceed to the next iteration without any modification, which ensures the fitness score is consistently dropping.\"; Sec. 3.4.2 Sentence-level (page 6): \"To further consider the potential instability of the fitness score in the optimization process, we incorporate a momentum-based design into the word scoring...\"; Alg. 5 LLM-based Diversification (Appendix B, page 15): \"messageuser ← 'Please revise the following sentence with no change to its length and only output the revised version, the sentence is: prompt'\" (shows mutation is constrained to generate fluent revisions); Appendix D (Implementation details, page 16): \"a mutation rate of 0.01\" (low per-step mutation probability); Table 1 (Attack Effectiveness and Stealthiness, page 7): shows PPL results where AutoDAN variants have low PPL comparable to handcrafted DAN (e.g., Handcrafted DAN PPL 22.97 vs AutoDAN-GA PPL ~37.49 and AutoDAN-HGA PPL ~46.47) and far lower than GCG (e.g., GCG PPL 1532.16 on Vicuna-7b), and Table 3 (page 8) demonstrates AutoDAN bypasses perplexity defense while GCG is strongly degraded—supporting that AutoDAN maintains natural, semantically-meaningful prompts across iterations."
